#### Unrealistic Goals for Employees
Background context explaining how managers setting unrealistic goals can lead to unethical behavior among employees. This is often due to the pressure to meet these goals, which may necessitate using unethical tactics.

If a sales quota can be met only through high-pressure, unethical sales tactics, employees will try to act "in the best interest of the company" and behave unethically. A manager who looks the other way when she or he knows about an employee's unethical behavior also sets an example indicating that ethical transgressions will be accepted.

:p What is a primary reason managers setting unrealistic goals can lead to unethical behavior among employees?
??x
Managers setting unrealistic goals can lead to unethical behavior because employees may feel pressured to meet these goals through means that violate company ethics. For instance, high-pressure sales tactics or cutting corners on quality control might become common practices.
```
// Example of a situation where unrealistic goals could pressure an employee:
public class SalesManager {
    public void setUnrealisticQuota(int quota) {
        // This method sets a very high sales target
        if (quota > 100) {
            System.out.println("Setting a very high sales target: " + quota);
        } else {
            System.out.println("Setting a realistic target.");
        }
    }
}
```
x??

#### Case in Point 3.5 - Morgan Stanley Smith Barney, LLC
Background context explaining the case involving Morgan Stanley Smith Barney and the sales contest that violated company policy.

Morgan Stanley Smith Barney had an internal policy against sales contests but branches in Massachusetts and Rhode Island still held one where brokers were incentivized with up to $5,000 for selling securities-based loans. The contest was conducted for nearly a year until it was stopped by Morgan Stanley’s compliance office. This case highlights how individual branches can circumvent company-wide policies.

:p What happened during the sales contest at Morgan Stanley Smith Barney that violated their internal policy?
??x
During the sales contest, brokers were incentivized with up to $5,000 for selling securities-based loans (SBLs). The contest ran for nearly a year and resulted in one branch tripling its loan volume. This practice was stopped by Morgan Stanley’s compliance office.

```
// Pseudocode representing the sales contest:
function runSalesContest(brokers) {
    for each broker in brokers {
        if (broker.soldSBLs > 50) { // Arbitrary threshold
            broker.incentive = calculateIncentive(broker.soldSBLs)
            if (broker.incentive >= $5,000) {
                announceWinner(broker.name);
                broker.awardIncentive();
            }
        }
    }
}
```
x??

#### Fostering of Unethical Conduct
Background context explaining how business owners and managers can actively foster unethical conduct, leading to negative consequences for the company.

Managers sometimes take more active roles in fostering unethical behavior, often with severe repercussions. This includes encouraging or enabling illegal practices that could harm the company’s reputation and financial stability.

:p How can business owners and managers contribute to fostering unethical conduct within a company?
??x
Business owners and managers can foster unethical conduct by actively promoting or ignoring unethical behaviors. For example, they might set unrealistic goals, create an environment where unethical behavior is tolerated, or even directly encourage illegal practices. Such actions can lead to serious consequences for the business, including lawsuits, loss of customer trust, and damage to the company’s reputation.

```
// Example of a manager fostering unethical conduct:
public class Manager {
    public void setUnrealisticGoals(int goal) {
        if (goal > 100) { // Setting an unrealistic sales target
            System.out.println("Setting an unrealistic sales goal: " + goal);
        } else {
            System.out.println("Setting a realistic sales target.");
        }
    }

    public void ignoreEthicalConcerns(EthicalIssue issue) {
        if (issue.isSevere()) { // Ignoring severe ethical issues
            System.out.println("Ignoring the severe ethical concern.");
        } else {
            handleIssue(issue);
        }
    }
}
```
x??

#### Case in Point 3.6 - Sonal Furniture and Custom Draperies, LLC
Background context explaining the case involving Sonal Furniture, where the owner, Shyam Garg, misled a couple into purchasing inferior quality furniture.

Dr. Rajendra Gandhi and his wife hired Sonal Furniture because of Garg’s cultural and religious connections but were later disappointed when the furniture was of very poor quality. The Gandhis eventually sued Garg and won in court, receiving a full refund and $100,000 in damages due to Garg's misrepresentations.

:p What legal action did Dr. Gandhi and his wife take against Sonal Furniture and Shyam Garg?
??x
Dr. Gandhi and his wife sued Sonal Furniture and Shyam Garg for misrepresentation and poor quality of the furniture. They won in court, receiving a full refund and $100,000 in damages.

```
// Pseudocode representing the lawsuit:
function fileSuit(defendant, plaintiff) {
    if (plaintiff.isDamaged()) { // Checking if the plaintiff is damaged
        fileLawsuit(plaintiff, defendant);
    } else {
        System.out.println("No legal action needed.");
    }
}

public class LegalAction {
    public void sueSonalFurniture() {
        fileSuit(SonalFurniture, DrGandhi);
    }
}
```
