#### Sheila's Will and Mental Capacity
Background context explaining the concept of wills, mental capacity, and intestacy laws. In this case, Sheila made a will leaving her property to Toby, Umeko, and Velda. However, two years later, she was adjudged mentally incompetent, and subsequently died.
:p Can Toby and Umeko have Sheila’s will revoked on the ground that she did not have the capacity to make a will? Why or why not?
??x
Toby and Umeko cannot revoke Sheila's will based on her lack of mental capacity at the time of making it. The law typically requires a will to be made when the testator (Sheila) had the required mental capacity, which includes understanding the nature and extent of their property and the people who might benefit from it. If Sheila was adjudged mentally incompetent after she made the will, this does not affect its validity as long as the will was executed properly at the time of its creation.

However, if Toby and Umeko can present evidence that Sheila lacked capacity when the will was created, they could potentially challenge the will through probate proceedings. But simply being adjudged incompetent later is insufficient to invalidate a will.
??x
